Section 9 of the Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996, deals with interim measures by a court. It states that a party may, before or during arbitral proceedings or at any time after the making of the award but before it is enforced, apply to a court for an interim measure of protection. 

The court may grant the following interim measures:
- to preserve the subject-matter of the dispute;
- to take interim custody of the subject-matter of the dispute or to take steps to preserve evidence;
- to provide for the sale of perishable goods;
- to secure the amount in dispute;
- to restrain a party from transferring, alienating, or disposing of assets;
- to restrain a party from changing the position regarding the subject-matter of the dispute;
- to appoint a guardian for a minor or person of unsound mind for the purposes of arbitral proceedings;
- to secure the presence of persons or the production of documents before the arbitral tribunal.

(Section 9, Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996)

In a murder trial under Indian law, the prosecution must prove the following essential elements beyond reasonable doubt:

1. The death of the victim (Section 299 of the Indian Penal Code, 1860 (IPC));
2. The act of the accused caused the death (Section 299 IPC);
3. The act was done with the intention of causing death or with the knowledge that it was likely to cause death (Section 299 IPC);
4. The accused had no valid defense, such as self-defense or insanity (Sections 96-106 IPC).

The prosecution must establish these elements through evidence and testimony, as held in numerous cases, including State of U.P. v. Krishna Master (2000) 9 SCC 414, where the Supreme Court emphasized the need for proof beyond reasonable doubt.

Under Section 11 of the Code of Civil Procedure (CPC), 1908, the ingredients of res judicata are:

1. The matter was directly and substantially in issue in the former suit (Section 11(a));
2. The former suit was between the same parties or between parties under whom they or any of them claim (Section 11(b));
3. The parties were litigating under the same title (Section 11(b));
4. The court that decided the former suit was competent to try the subsequent suit (Section 11(c));
5. The matter was heard and finally decided by the court in the former suit (Section 11(d)).

If these conditions are met, the matter is said to be res judicata, or "a thing already judged," and cannot be relitigated in a subsequent suit. (Section 11, CPC, 1908)

Under Section 6 of the Transfer of Property Act, 1882, the following kinds of property cannot be transferred:

1. The interest of a lessee under a lease of immovable property (Section 6(a));
2. The interest of a tenant under a tenancy agreement, where the tenant has no right to assign or sublet (Section 6(b));
3. An interest in a property that is held for a public purpose or as a public trust (Section 6(c) and (d) - now omitted);
4. A mere right to sue (Section 6(e));
5. A right to future maintenance (Section 6(f));
6. A mere right to revenge (Section 6(g) - now omitted);
7. Any estate which is vested in the State, or in any other public person, or in any officer, by virtue of his office (Section 6(h) - now omitted, but similar provisions exist in other laws);
8. A right to property which is inalienable by reason of a statutory provision (Section 6, general principle).

These provisions restrict the transfer of certain types of property to prevent unjust or undesirable outcomes.

Under Section 2(68) of the Companies Act, 2013, a private company is defined as a company that has a minimum paid-up share capital of ₹1 lakh or such higher paid-up share capital as may be prescribed, and which by its articles—

(a) restricts the right to transfer its shares;
(b) except in the case of One Person Company, limits the number of its members to two hundred;
(c) prohibits any invitation to the public to subscribe for any securities of the company.

Under Section 9 of the Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996, a party can seek interim measures from the court before, during, or after the arbitration proceedings. These measures include:

1. Appointment of a guardian for a minor or person of unsound mind (Section 9(1)(a));
2. Preservation, interim custody, or sale of any goods which are the subject-matter of the arbitration agreement (Section 9(1)(b));
3. Securing the amount in dispute in the arbitration (Section 9(1)(c));
4. Detention, preservation, or inspection of any property or thing which is the subject-matter of the arbitration agreement (Section 9(1)(d));
5. Interim injunction or the appointment of a receiver (Section 9(1)(e));
6. Such other interim measure of protection as may appear to the court to be just and convenient (Section 9(1)(f)).

The court may grant these interim measures to prevent any of the parties from frustrating the arbitration process or to protect the subject-matter of the dispute. (Section 9, Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996)

Under Section 37 of the Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996, the following orders are appealable:

1. Refusing to refer the parties to arbitration under Section 8 (Order refusing reference to arbitration);
2. Granting or refusing to grant any interim measure under Section 9 (Interim measures by Court);
3. Refusing to enforce a foreign award under Section 36 (Enforcement of foreign awards), after the award has become enforceable under Section 35 (Enforcement of foreign awards - conditions) and Section 36 read with Section 48 (Conditions for enforcement of foreign awards);
4. Setting aside or refusing to set aside an arbitral award under Section 34 (Application for setting aside arbitral award).

These orders are appealable to the Court as per Section 37 of the Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996.

Under Section 3 of the Protection of Women from Domestic Violence Act, 2005, domestic violence is defined as any act of commission or omission which aids or abets the commission of, or which is an incident of, domestic violence, including but not limited to:

(a) physical abuse;
(b) sexual abuse;
(c) verbal and emotional abuse;
(d) economic abuse; and
(e) harassment with the intent to coerce the victim to meet any unlawful demand for any dowry or other property or valuable security.

This definition is provided under Section 3 of the Act, which aims to protect women from domestic violence in India.

Under Section 19 of the Protection of Women from Domestic Violence Act, 2005, the following residence orders are available:

1. Restraining the respondent from dispossessing or in any other manner disturbing the possession of the shared household (Section 19(a));
2. Directing the respondent to remove himself from the shared household (Section 19(b));
3. Restraining the respondent or any of his relatives from entering any portion of the shared household in which the petitioner resides (Section 19(c));
4. Restraining the respondent from alienating any assets in the shared household (Section 19(d));
5. Directing the respondent to secure same level of alternative accommodation for the petitioner (Section 19(e));
6. Providing temporary custody of any child or children to the petitioner (Section 19(f));
7. Directing the respondent to pay monetary relief to the petitioner (Section 20, but can be read with Section 19 for residence orders).

These orders aim to provide protection and relief to the victim of domestic violence, ensuring her right to reside in the shared household.

